<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How wide should quilt binding strips be?", answer: "The most common binding strip width is 2.5 inches for a double-fold (French) binding that finishes at about 3/8 of an inch on the front and back of the quilt. Some quilters prefer 2.25 inches for a tighter, more traditional look, or 2.75 inches for a fuller binding that shows more fabric on the front. The width also depends on the thickness of your batting — thicker batting needs wider strips to wrap around the edge comfortably." },
  { question: "How many strips do I need for a twin-size quilt?", answer: "A standard twin quilt is roughly 70 by 90 inches, giving a perimeter of 320 inches. With 10 inches of overage for corners and joining, you need 330 inches of binding total. Dividing by the 42-inch usable width of standard quilting cotton gives about 8 strips. At 2.5 inches wide, that is 20 inches of fabric, or roughly 5/8 of a yard. Always round up and buy a little extra in case of mistakes." },
  { question: "What's the difference between bias and straight binding?", answer: "Straight-grain binding is cut across the width of the fabric (cross-grain) and is the most common choice because it is fast, uses less fabric, and works well for quilts with straight edges. Bias binding is cut at a 45-degree angle and has more stretch, making it the right choice for quilts with curved or scalloped edges. Bias binding also wears more durably along the quilt edge because multiple threads cross each friction point." },
  { question: "Should I join binding strips with a straight or diagonal seam?", answer: "Always join binding strips with a diagonal seam at a 45-degree angle. Diagonal seams distribute bulk across a wider area so they lie flat and are virtually invisible in the finished binding. Straight seams create a stiff ridge that stands out visually and can interfere with the binding folding smoothly around the edge. Trim the seam to 1/4 inch and press open for the flattest result." },
  { question: "Can I use scraps for binding?", answer: "Yes — scrappy bindings are a classic look, especially for utility quilts, charity quilts, and memory quilts. Collect strips of any leftover binding-width fabric, join them with diagonal seams, and go around the quilt as usual. For a planned scrappy look, sort the scraps into a repeating color sequence. For a random scrappy look, grab and sew without thinking about order." }
]) %>

